<p class="standfirst">The son of a pensioner who was killed after a collision with a speeding cyclist has told LBC that “something has to change” after there was no prosecution.</p>
<div class="remixd-audio-player-wrapper">
<h4 class="remixd-audio-player-wrapper__header">
        Listen to this article
    </h4>
<div id="remixd-audio-player">
<div id="remixd-audio-loading">Loading audio...</div>
</div>
</div>
<p class="paragraph-text">Brian Fitzgerald, a vice president at Credit Suisse, avoided conviction because speed limits do not apply to cyclists in the same way as motorists, a court heard.</p><div id="Teads_ad1"></div><p class="paragraph-text">Mr Fitzgerald was doing laps of Regent’s Park as part of a “fast group” of cyclists when he collided with Hilder Griffiths, 81, who was crossing the road to a pedestrian island.</p><p class="paragraph-text">Despite the 20mph speed limit, Mr Fitzgerald told a coroner the group were travelling up to 29pmh in a “pace line” when he struck the retired nursery teacher from Marylebone who was walking her dog.</p><p class="paragraph-text">Mrs Griffiths’ son, Gerard, 52, told Matthew Wright on LBC: “The park is used mainly by families with children, people with dogs. I’m sure my mum is not the first one to be encountering a group like this but she is the first one to be killed by one.</p><div data-openweb-ad data-row="1" data-column="1"></div><p class="paragraph-text">“Something has to change across the board with the law, not just for the speed limit of parks, it’s got to be in general.</p><p class="paragraph-text">“It’s a culture that has grown over the years and it was inevitably going to happen. Unfortunately, my mother was the victim of it but at some point, something like that was going to happen because they neither have the will nor obligation to stop.”</p>
<figure>
<img loading="lazy" alt="Hilda Griffiths" class="content-image" data-image-catalogue-id="649616" width="660" height="370" src="https://images.lbc.co.uk/images/649616?crop=16_9&amp;width=660&amp;relax=1&amp;format=webp&amp;signature=KYQt0UTKzPWBbLs1iIuTBBweVfU=" srcset="
                https://images.lbc.co.uk/images/649616?crop=16_9&amp;width=375&amp;relax=1&amp;format=webp&amp;signature=UNlF488XA9GQ08uyaVbPjdh8uH8= 375w,
                https://images.lbc.co.uk/images/649616?crop=16_9&amp;width=420&amp;relax=1&amp;format=webp&amp;signature=R6MzsgD-I-VZ9ZpEzJwIuuovCtw= 420w,
                https://images.lbc.co.uk/images/649616?crop=16_9&amp;width=660&amp;relax=1&amp;format=webp&amp;signature=KYQt0UTKzPWBbLs1iIuTBBweVfU= 660w" sizes="
                (max-width: 375px) 375px,
                (max-width: 420px) 420px,
                660px" />
<figcaption>
    Hilda Griffiths.
    <span class="attribution">
        Picture: 
Supplied


    </span>
</figcaption>
</figure>
<p class="paragraph-text">Mr Fitzgerald said there was “zero reaction time” and that the cyclists did not need to obey the 20mph limit as “the legal speed limit does not apply to cyclists (the same) as motorists”.</p><p class="paragraph-text">Police concluded there was “insufficient evidence for a real prospect of conviction” and the case was closed with “no further action”.</p>
<div class="dac__article-mpu">
